Strictly-monotonic commit timestamps for Link client-state writes.

Bug: two commit*SessionState calls within the same wall-clock
microsecond produce identical IncomingClientState timestamps. Link's
selectPreferredStartStopState uses `>` (strict greater-than), so on a
timestamp tie the OLD state wins and the NEW state is silently dropped.

Symptom in SuperSonic: rapid setIsPlaying(true)/setIsPlaying(false)
sequences silently drop the second call — observable as a unit-test
failure (test_superclock.cpp:53 setIsPlaying round-trips) but the
same race can hit any application code that issues multiple state
mutations between audio callbacks.

Fix: bump the commit timestamp through a process-wide atomic monotonic
counter, so every commit's timestamp is strictly greater than every
prior commit's. Conceptually equivalent to
  max(mClock.micros(), lastCommitMicros + 1).

Targets both code paths: commitAppSessionState (app thread, called by
setIsPlaying/setTempo/etc.) and commitAudioSessionState (audio thread,
RT-safe — atomic CAS is lock-free with bounded retries).

Compatibility: timestamps remain in mClock's micros domain (at most
~N microseconds ahead of wall clock if a burst of N writes lands in
one microsecond, then re-converges on the next tick). Wire protocol
unchanged. Single-write-per-microsecond case is unaffected.

Pinned to Link-4.0.

--- a/include/ableton/Link.ipp
+++ b/include/ableton/Link.ipp
@@ -20,12 +20,31 @@
 #pragma once
 
 #include <ableton/link/Phase.hpp>
+#include <algorithm>
+#include <atomic>
 
 namespace ableton
 {
 namespace detail
 {
 
+// SUPERSONIC PATCH: monotonically-advancing commit timestamps. Ensures
+// rapid-succession client-state writes don't tie on integer-microsecond
+// rounding, which would let selectPreferredStartStopState drop the
+// later write. Process-wide because timestamps are in mClock's domain
+// (mach_absolute_time on macOS) which is itself process-wide.
+inline std::chrono::microseconds monotonicCommitTimestamp(
+  const std::chrono::microseconds now)
+{
+  static std::atomic<int64_t> sLastCommitMicros{0};
+  int64_t cur = sLastCommitMicros.load(std::memory_order_relaxed);
+  int64_t want;
+  do { want = std::max(now.count(), cur + 1); }
+  while (!sLastCommitMicros.compare_exchange_weak(
+      cur, want, std::memory_order_relaxed));
+  return std::chrono::microseconds(want);
+}
+
 template <typename Clock>
 inline typename BasicLink<Clock>::SessionState toSessionState(
   const link::ClientState& state, const bool isConnected)
@@ -150,7 +169,8 @@
   const typename BasicLink<Clock>::SessionState state)
 {
   mController.setClientStateRtSafe(
-    detail::toIncomingClientState(state.mState, state.mOriginalState, mClock.micros()));
+    detail::toIncomingClientState(state.mState, state.mOriginalState,
+      detail::monotonicCommitTimestamp(mClock.micros())));
 }
 
 template <typename Clock>
@@ -165,7 +185,8 @@
   const typename BasicLink<Clock>::SessionState state)
 {
   mController.setClientState(
-    detail::toIncomingClientState(state.mState, state.mOriginalState, mClock.micros()));
+    detail::toIncomingClientState(state.mState, state.mOriginalState,
